\begin_layout Section
STAR experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Solenoidal Tracker at RHIC (STAR) is one of the two large detecter systems
 constructed at RHIC.
 Heavy ion collision at RHIC creates a nuclear environment of a large produced
 particles (up to approximately 1000 per unit pseudo-rapidity) and high
 momentum particles from hard parton-parton scattering.
 The main physics goal of the STAR experiment is to measure many observables
 simultaneously to investigate the signatures of a possible QGP phase transition
 and to understand the space-time evolution of the collision process in
 ultra-relativistic heavy ion collisions.
 In order to accomplish this, STAR was designed primarily for measurements
 of hadron production over a large solid angle.
 The STAR detector systems are very effective in high precision tracking,
 momentum analysis, and particle identification at the central rapidity
 region.
 With the installation of the Time Of Flight detector (TOF) in 2009, STAR
 gained the capability to identify electrons and positions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
STAR has an azimuthal symmetric acceptance and covers large range around
 mid-rapidity (
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|$
\end_inset

<1, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 azimuthal coverage).
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: STAR det"

\end_inset

 shows the layout of the STAR detector systems alone with the subsystems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Close to the beam pipe is the Heavy Flavor Tracker (HFT) which is a new
 detector add in the STAR detector systems in 2014.
 The HFT is designed to measure the heavy flavor production by the measurement
 of displaced vertices and to do the direct topological identification of
 open charm hadrons.
 The Time Projection Chamber (TPC) is the main tracker at STAR which has
 a coverage of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|$
\end_inset

<1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 in azimuthal direction.
 The Time Of Flight (TOF) detector is surrounding the TPC which has also
 a coverage 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|$
\end_inset

<1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 in azimuthal direction.
 The Barrel Electro-Magnetic Calorimeter (BEMC) located outside of the TOF
 and covers 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|<1$
\end_inset

 with complete azimuthal symmetry.
 The Endcap Electro-Magnetic Calorimeter (EEMC) covers for 1 < |η| < 2,
 over the full azimuthal range.
 The EMCs are used to distinguish high momentum single photons from photon
 pairs of π and η meson decays and electrons from charged hadrons.
 Outside the BEMC is the magnet system which provides a uniform magnetic
 field parallel to the beam direction and together with BEMC it also servers
 as the electron and hadron absorber for the Muon Telescope Detector (MTD).
 The MTD is also a new added detector, which is installed in 2014.
 It is designed to detect high 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{T}$
\end_inset

 muon for heavy flavor collectivity and production.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Along the beam pipe, there are some trigger detectors: Zero Degree Calorimeter
 (ZDC), Vertex Position Detector (VPD) and Beam-Beam Counter (BBC).
 Two ZDCs locates on each side ~ 18 m away from the collision point.
 The ZDCs are designed as hadronic calorimeters to detect the outgoing neutrons.
 Dipole magnets are put before the ZDC detectors to bend away the charged
 fragments.
 The ZDC signals are used for monitoring the heavy ion beam luminosity and
 for the experiments triggers.
 The BBC subsystem covers 
\begin_inset Formula $3.3<|\eta|<5.0$
\end_inset

 and consists of two disk shaped scintillating detectors.
 They are placed at the endcaps of the TPC (3.5 m from TPC center).
 Each BBC disk is made up of close packed hexagonal scintillator tiles in
 two rings.
 A BBC trigger corresponds to a prompt coincidence between at least one
 (out of eighteen total) tile firing in both BBC EAST and BBC WEST within
 a time window.
 This BBC trigger defines a minimum bias trigger corresponding to a p-p
 cross section of 
\begin_inset Formula $\thickapprox$
\end_inset

 26 mb, 87% of the p-p Non-Singly Diffractive (NSD) inelastic cross section.
 The VPD detector has two assembly which consists of two rings of readout
 detectors (19 channels).
 The two assemblies are mounted symmetrically with respect to the center
 of STAR at a distance of 5.7 m and cover 
\begin_inset Formula $4.24≤\eta≤5.1$
\end_inset

.
 The signals from VPD are used to select minimum bias collisions, to constrain
 the location of the primary collision vertex along the beam pipe and to
 provide start time for STAR fast timing detectors.
 EMCs is also used to trigger on high 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{T}$
\end_inset

 particle events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detectors involved in this analysis will be introduced in detail in
 follow sections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../fig/2.Detector/STAR det.png
	width 80text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The STAR detectors.
 HFT and MTD are new added detectors and were fully installed in 2014.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: STAR det"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
STAR magnet system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The STAR magnet system (cite) is a room temperature solenoidal magnet which
 was designed as a cylinder with a length of 6.85 m and has inner and outer
 diameter of 5.27 m and 7.32 m, respectively.
 It provides an uniform magnetic field which parallels to the beam direction
 (Z direction) with a maximum value 0.5 T for charged particle momentum analysis.
 STAR magnet can work under full field (+0.5 T), reversed full field (-0.5
 T) and half field configuration (
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

0.25 T).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Main tracker - Time Projection Chamber
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Time Projection Chamber (TPC) is the primary tracking detector and the
 heart of STAR detector system.
 The TPC was designed to record the tracks of particles, measure their momenta,
 and provide particle identification by measuring their ionization energy
 loss (
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
).
 It has a large acceptance around middle rapidity (
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|<1.8$
\end_inset

 ) and full azimuthal coverage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TPC"

\end_inset

 shows the STAR TPC.
 It was built as a cylinder with a length of 4.2 m and outer diameter of
 4 m and inner diameter of 1 m.
 TPC was installed inside the STAR magnet system which provides a 0.5 T uniform
 magnetic field.
 The beam pipe which is alone the Z direction goes through the center axis
 of TPC and concentric with TPC.
 The collisions happens in side the beam pipe near the center of TPC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inside the TPC, it is an empty volume which is filled with P10 gas (10%
 methane, 90% argon) regulated at 2 mbar above atmospheric pressure.
 There is a well defined, uniform, electric field of 
\begin_inset Formula $\thickapprox$
\end_inset

135 V/cm in the volume serve as the drift field.
 The primary advantage of P10 gas is that electrons has a fast drift velocity
 which peaks at a low electric field which makes the drift velocity stable
 and insensitive to small changes in temperature and pressure.
 The uniform drift field in TPC is defined by a thin conductive Central
 Membrane (CM) at the center of the TPC, concentric field-cage cylinders
 and the readout end caps (cite).
 The central membrane is operated at 28 kV and the end caps are at ground.
 The typical drift velocity of electrons in the STAR TPC is 5.45 cm/
\begin_inset Formula $\mu s$
\end_inset

.
 The transverse diffusion is 230 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m/\sqrt{cm}$
\end_inset

 and the longitudinal diffusion is 360 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m/\sqrt{cm}$
\end_inset

 with 140V/cm drift field and 0.5 T magnetic field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The STAR TPC's readout system is based on Multi-Wire Proportional Chambers
 (MWPC) with readout pads.
 The readout planes are arranged as on a clock with 12 sectors around the
 circle at each end of TPC.
 The readout system includes four components: a pad plane and three wire
 planes, shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:outer_wires"

\end_inset

.
 The anode wire plane of 20 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

 wires with the pad plane on one side and the ground wire plane on the other
 composes the amplification readout layer.
 It can provide an amplification of 1000 to 3000 while the drifting electrons
 avalanche in the high fields.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pad_plane"

\end_inset

 shows the anode pad plane with one full sector.
 To optimize the 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
resolution, the outer sector was designed to have continuous pad coverage.
 This setup can improve statistics on the 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
measurement because the full track ionization signal is collected with more
 ionization electrons.
 The inner sub sectors are in the region of highest track density.
 The design of inner pads is optimized for good two-hit resolution by using
 smaller pads with separate pad rows instead of continuous pad coverage.
 The third wire plane is a gating grid which is a gate to control electrons
 from TPC drift volume to MWPC.
 It also stops the positive ions inside MWPC from entering the drift volume
 to preserve the uniform drift field (cite).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the charged particles travel through the gas volume, they liberate
 electrons from the gas molecules due to ionization energy loss.
 The released secondary electrons drift under the drift field to the ends
 of TPC and collected by the readout system.
 The signals then are digitalized and transmitted to STAR Data AcQuistion
 system (DAQ).
 These raw signals (ADC and TDC) are reconstructed into 3D position informations
 of the ionization (hit positions) by a Kalman filte with a typical resolution
 0.5~1.0 mm.
 The tracks of particles are reconstructed with high precision from these
 hits informations in 3 dimension by Time Projection chamber Tracker (TPT)
 algorithm.
 These tracks are combined with other available tracking detector's results
 and refit by a Kalman filter routine.
 Then the primary collision vertex is reconstructed from these global tracks.
 The primary vertex resolution is ~ 350 μm with more than 1000 tracks.
 Furthermore, tracks with the 
\emph on
distance of closest approach
\emph default
 (dca) to the primary vertex less then 3 cm is refitted by forcing the track
 to originate from the primary vertex, these tracks are called primary tracks
 which has improved resolution in position and momentum due to the relatively
 high precision of primary vertex.
 The reconstruction efficiency including the detector acceptance for primary
 tracks depends on the particle type, track quality cuts, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{T}$
\end_inset

, track multiplicity etc.
 The typical value for the primary pions with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{fit}$
\end_inset

 > 24 and |
\begin_inset Formula $η$
\end_inset

| < 0.7, dca < 3.0 cm is approximate constant at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{T}$
\end_inset

 > 0.4 GeV/c: 
\begin_inset Formula $>∼$
\end_inset

 90% for Au + Au peripheral collisions and ~ 80% for central collisions,
 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the collected ionization energy loss (
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
) information, TPC also provides capability for particle identification.
 The mean rate of 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
is given by the Bethe-Bloch equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Bethe-Bloch"

\end_inset

 (cite):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{dE}{dx}=Kz^{2}\frac{Z}{A}\frac{1}{\beta^{2}}\left[\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{2m_{e}c^{2}\beta^{2}\gamma^{2}T_{max}}{I^{2}}-\beta^{2}-\frac{\delta}{2}\right]\label{eq: Bethe-Bloch}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and furthermore optimized by the Bichsel functions (cite SN0439 NIM A 562
 (2006) 154-197).
 For each track, 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
is extracted from the deposit charge collected on the pad rows up to 45.
 Energy loss of a charged particle for a given track length can be described
 by the Bichsel function (cite).
 However, the mean of the distribution is sensitive to the fluctuations
 in the tail of the distribution.
 Therefore, the most probable 
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
 is measured by removing the highest 30% of the measured clusters.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dEdx_Bichsel"

\end_inset

 shows the 70% truncated mean dE/dx distribution as well as the expectation
 from Bichsel functions.
 Clearly the energy loss is different corresponding to different particle
 species at the same momentum.
 In Au+Au 200 GeV collision, STAR can separate 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 up to ~ 0.7 GeV/c and identify proton up to ~ 1.1 GeV/c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
 calibration
\series default
 is performed for each run setups respect to collision type, collision energy
 and magnetic field.
 The calibration is done with a specified data sample selected by following
 requirement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Good clusters : used in track fit, without overlaps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Good global tracks : with track length in TPC > 20 (or 40) cm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tracks with 0.4 < p < 0.5 GeV/c (~MIP for pions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\gamma=p/m=4$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 can be well separated from other particles and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\gamma$
\end_inset

 dependence of 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
is completely defined by Bichsel model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $dE/dx$
\end_inset

 calibration process contains a lot of corrections due to the energy loss
 in TPC is influenced by many factors, but usually it can be separated into
 three step: a over all correction of gas gains for sectors and rows; correction
 for gas pressure dependence; correction of track length.
 A value 
\emph on
Z 
\emph default
is defined as flowing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z_{\pi}=log\left(\frac{dE/dx_{measure}}{dE/dx_{Bichsel}^{\pi}}\right)\label{eq:Zpi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $dE/dx_{Bichsel}^{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is the predicted for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 from Bichsel model.
 The 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
distributions are parameterized by a 5 gaussians fit with respect to mean
 position (
\begin_inset Formula $μ$
\end_inset

) and width (
\begin_inset Formula $σ$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $π$
\end_inset

, which contain contribution from 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 The relative positions of other particles to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are fixed.
 And the position (
\begin_inset Formula $μ$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 defines the calibration correction.
 The correction parameters are defined which provide condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and variation is within 1% level.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SecRow_24_40"

\end_inset

 shows an example of the 5 gaussians fit for sector 24 row 40 in Run11 p+p
 500 GeV collisions.
 The calibration is separated into 4 passes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
pass 0: Gas gain correction for sector/row.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 distributions are parameterized in each sector and row.
 The correction is defined to direction shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to 0 for each sector and row which generates a correction table.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SecRowCor"

\end_inset

 shows the variation vs Sector and Row before correction (before) and after
 correction (after).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
pass 1: Dependence of gas gain on gas density due to pressure.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:PresureCor"

\end_inset

 shows the 
\begin_inset Formula $dE/dx$
\end_inset

 variation vs gas pressure before and after the correction.
 A linear fit is used to parameterize pressure dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $dE/dx$
\end_inset

 variation and to define the correction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
pass 2: Dependence of the truncated mean for track's 
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
 and its relative error versus track length in TPC.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TrackLengthCor"

\end_inset

 shows the track length dependence before correction and after correction.
 Usually a polynomial function is used to define the correction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
pass 3: Final pass to check the calibration results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corrections are not independent with each other, so after each new pass,
 the results for previous correction need to be checked.
 If the variation is larger than 1%, another pass is need to redone previous
 correction.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dEdx_Calib_procedure"

\end_inset

 shows the procedure of 
\emph on
dE/dx 
\emph default
calibration.
 The requirement for dE/dx resolution achievable with our calibration procedure
 has been set as 7.5% for tracks with length in TPC equal to 76.2 cm.
 Here take the calibration for p+p 500GeV in Run11 as an example, without
 any correction the 
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
 resolution for tracks with 76.3 cm length in TPC is 7.73% and the one with
 all corrections is 6.82% (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dEdxRes"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

