\begin_layout Subsection
Time Of Flight system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Time of Flight System is another important set of detectors used in
 this analysis.
 The TOF system is designed to measure the flight time of charged particles.
 Combining with path length of tracks reconstructed by TPC, it can provide
 the velocity of the charge particles which is used to identify charged
 particles.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dEdx_Bichsel"

\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
dE/dx
\emph default
 binds of different particles cross with each other in some momentum regions
 where they can not be separated by using
\emph on
 dE/dx 
\emph default
only.
 With the installation of TOF, these holes are covered by adding the flight
 velocity into the PID criteria.
 Therefore, TOF greatly improves the PID capability of STAR and makes the
 identification of electron and position from the hadron background possible
 for the STAR detector system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The TOF consists of the barrel Time Of Flight detector (bTOF) and the the
 Vertex Position Detector (VPD).
 The bTOF is surrounding the TPC and measures the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stop
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 time (the time charged particle reach bTOF).
 The pVPD consists of two identical detector assemblies that are positioned
 very close to the beam pipe and outside the STAR magnet.
 It measures the start time (the time when the collision happens).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bTOF is based on the Multi-gap Resistive Plate Chamber (MRPC) technology
 which is first developed by the CERN ALICE group (cite).
 MRPC technology is capable to provide the necessary timing resolution with
 a relative low cost.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MRPC"

\end_inset

 shows the side view of an MRPC module appropriate for STAR.
 Basically, the MRPC is a stack of resistive plates arranged in parallel.
 These plates are separated by nylon fishing line and form a series of uniform
 gas gaps with a width of 0.22 mm.
 The internal resistive plates are 20 cm long and 6.1 cm wide and 0.54 mm
 thick, which has a resist of 
\begin_inset Formula $8\times10^{12}\;\Omega\cdot cm$
\end_inset

.
 The external plates are 
\begin_inset Formula $20.6\; cm\times7.6\; cm\times1.1\; mm$
\end_inset

 with electrodes on the outer surface.
 High voltage is applied on these electrodes to generate a uniform strong
 electric field in each sub-gap.
 All the internal plates are electrically floating.
 When charged particles go through the chamber, they generates avalanches
 in the gas gaps.
 The resistive plates are transparent to charge induction from avalanches
 in the gaps.
 Thus the signal collected on the copper pickup pads is the sum of possible
 avalanches from all gas gaps.
 The typical size of a MRPC module is 
\begin_inset Formula $94\: mm\times212\: mm\times12\; mm$
\end_inset

 and the active area is 
\begin_inset Formula $61\; mm\times200\; mm$
\end_inset

, and has 6 readout pads which has an area of 
\begin_inset Formula $63\; mm\times31.4\; mm$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $3\; mm$
\end_inset

 gaps between pads.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One TOF tray consists of 32 MRPC modules which are installed alone the beam
 direction.
 Every modules contains 6 read out units (cell/channel).
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TOFTray"

\end_inset

 shows the structure of a STAR-TOF tray.
 The bTOF contains 120 trays in total and has a coverage of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 in azimuthal direction and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|<0.9$
\end_inset

 in beam direction.
 The first prototypes of TOF were installed in year 2003.
 72% of the bTOF were installed in 2009 and fully installed with 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 azimuthal coverage in 2010.
 The typical time resolution of TOF system is smaller than 100 ps.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1/beta_TOF"

\end_inset

 shows the inverse velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

) distribution as a function of momentum.
 With the installation of TOF, the momentum range of separating 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is improved from 0.7 GeV/c to 1.8 GeV/c, and proton identification range
 is improved from 1.1 GeV/c to 3 GeV/c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

